# sessions-explained.tflw — SPEC §3.3: a `session` block is tflw's one auth concept. It's a
# named sequence of steps (usually a login) that runs once per run per worker and is cached; a
# test opts in with `as <session-name>` and starts with the session's declared headers/cookies
# already applied. tflw.config (this repo's) defines two: `admin` (bearer) and `shopper` (cookie).
#
# `as admin, shopper` (decision 96, closes TFLW-GAPS.md gap #7) opts into *both* at once — every
# opted-in session's headers/cookies merge into the test's starting state, later-listed session
# winning any header/cookie-name conflict against an earlier one. See interleaved-sessions.tflw
# for the realistic version of this (a real cross-identity workflow); this file keeps it minimal.

@examples @sessions
test "opting into `as admin` starts every api step with the admin session's bearer header already applied" as admin
  # No explicit Authorization header anywhere below — `as admin` supplied it before this test's
  # first step even ran (tflw.config's `session admin` block captured it once for the whole run).
  api GET /orders/all
  expect status equals 200

@examples @sessions
test "opting into `as shopper` starts with the cookie jar already carrying the session's cookie" as shopper
  api GET /auth/profile
  expect status equals 200
  expect body.role equals "user"

@examples @sessions
test "a test with no `as <session>` clause is anonymous — no auth applied at all"
  api GET /orders/all
  expect status equals 401

@examples @sessions @regression
test "as admin, shopper opts into both at once — both sessions' contributions land on this test" as admin, shopper
  # admin's bearer header applies with no override, exactly as `as admin` alone would.
  api GET /orders/all
  expect status equals 200

  # apiV2's guard checks a bearer header before a cookie, so with both sessions merged onto every
  # step by default, admin's bearer would otherwise always win — an explicit per-step `header
  # "Authorization" is ""` clears it just for this one request, letting the guard fall through to
  # shopper's cookie (per-step headers are the highest-precedence layer, SPEC §3.3).
  api GET /auth/profile
    header "Authorization" is ""
  expect status equals 200
  expect body.role equals "user"
